{{Infobox scientist | name = | image = <!--(as myimage.jpg, no 'File:')--> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1921|08|16|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Glarus]], [[Switzerland]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2009|01|30|1921|08|16|df=y}} | death_place = [[Küssnacht]], [[Switzerland]] | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} --> | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = | fields = | workplaces = [[University of Lausanne]], [[ETH Zürich]] | alma_mater = [[ETH Zürich]] | thesis_title = Der Lias der Glarner Alpen | thesis_url = | thesis_year = 1947 | doctoral_advisor = | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | influences = | influenced = | awards = [[Gustav-Steinmann-Medaille]] {{small|(1998)}} | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} --> | footnotes = | spouse = }} '''Rudolf Trümpy''' (16 August 1921 – 30 January 2009)<ref name="French">{{cite web|url=http://www.academie-sciences.fr/membres/T/Trumpy_Rudolf.htm|title=Rudolf Trümpy|work=Membres|publisher=Académie des sciences|language=French|accessdate=2010-07-31|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100927000949/http://www.academie-sciences.fr/membres/T/Trumpy_Rudolf.htm|archivedate=2010-09-27}}</ref> was a [[Swiss people|Swiss]] [[geologist]], who was born in the small Swiss town of [[Glarus]]. He graduated from the [[ETH Zürich]] in the late 1940s with a thesis titled: “Der Lias der Glarner Alpen”. From 1947 to 1953 he spent his post-doctoral years in [[Lausanne]] before being appointed professor at ETH Zürich in 1953. He would remain there until 1986.
His research mainly concentrated on [[alpine geology]]. However, he also published papers on extra-alpine regions like [[Greenland]], the [[Montagne Noire]] and the [[Sahara]]. He was the author of the reference book ''Geology of Switzerland''.
Trümpy is the recipient of numerous awards and prizes including the [[Wollaston Medal]]<ref name="Wollaston">{{cite web|url=http://www.geolsoc.org.uk/gsl/info/collections/archives/page750.html|title=Wollaston Medal|publisher=[[Geological Society of London]]|accessdate=2009-02-03|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090124005509/http://www.geolsoc.org.uk/gsl/info/collections/archives/page750.html|archivedate=2009-01-24|df=}}</ref> and the [[Penrose Medal]].<ref name="Penrose">{{cite web|url=http://www.geosociety.org/awards/past.htm#penrose|title=Past Award & Medal Recipients - Penrose Medal|publisher=[[Geological Society of America]]|accessdate=2009-02-03}}</ref> In 1978 he was elected a Foreign Associate of the [[United States National Academy of Sciences]].<ref name="NAS">{{cite web|url=http://www.nasonline.org/site/Dir/1589208854?pg=vprof&mbr=1005562&returl=http://www.nasonline.org/site/Dir/1589208854%3Fpg%3Dsrch%26view%3Dbasic&retmk=search_again_link|title=Trumpy, D. Rudolf|work=Membership Directory|publisher=[[United States National Academy of Sciences]]|accessdate=2009-02-03}}</ref> He is also a member of the [[French Academy of Sciences]].<ref name="French"/>
Many stratigraphic formations in the western Alps were first described by Trümpy. For example, the [[Couches de l’Aroley Formation|Couches de l’Aroley]], the [[Couches des Marmontains Formation|Couches des Marmontains]] and the [[Couches de St-Cristoph Formation|Couches de St Cristoph]].<ref name=stratigraphie.ch>{{cite web|title=Lithostratigraphisches Lexikon der Schweiz|url=http://www.stratigraphie.ch/?page=strat&strat=Penninikum_W|work=Penninikum|publisher=stratigraphie.ch|accessdate=25 February 2013}}</ref>
